1
00:00:05,255 --> 00:00:07,216
(CLOCK CHIMES)

2
00:00:11,136 --> 00:00:12,763
Whoever those aliens are,
they haven't just arrived,

3
00:00:12,846 --> 00:00:13,931
they've been here for a while.

4
00:00:14,264 --> 00:00:16,433
Harriet Jones,
MP for Flydale North.

5
00:00:16,683 --> 00:00:19,353
I thought
I was Prime Minister now.

6
00:00:26,944 --> 00:00:29,071
(SCREAMING)

7
00:00:30,447 --> 00:00:33,784
Thank you all for wearing
your ID cards.

8
00:00:35,410 --> 00:00:37,663
They'll help to identify
the bodies.

9
00:00:38,038 --> 00:00:39,706
(ALL SCREAMING)

10
00:00:42,793 --> 00:00:44,419
(GROANING)

11
00:00:56,306 --> 00:00:58,267
Deadly to humans, maybe.

12
00:01:01,937 --> 00:01:03,605
(ALIEN SHRIEKING)

13
00:01:06,858 --> 00:01:08,569
(DOCTOR WHO THEME)

14
00:01:42,728 --> 00:01:44,354
(ALIEN SHRIEKING)

15
00:01:50,110 --> 00:01:52,362
(ELECTRICITY SURGING)

16
00:02:05,626 --> 00:02:07,044
Ah!

17
00:02:17,346 --> 00:02:18,722
Jackie!

18
00:02:21,725 --> 00:02:23,769
(ALIEN ROARS)

19
00:02:31,652 --> 00:02:32,653
(CAMERA CLICKS)

20
00:02:33,278 --> 00:02:34,905
(ALIEN SCREECHES)

21
00:02:36,865 --> 00:02:38,116
Oi, you want aliens,
you've got them.

22
00:02:38,200 --> 00:02:40,494
They're inside Downing Street.
Come on.

23
00:02:43,580 --> 00:02:45,499
(SHRIEKING CONTINUES)

24
00:02:53,423 --> 00:02:56,802
Reinstate my disguise!
Hurry up, hurry! Hurry!

25
00:03:00,263 --> 00:03:01,556
No, wait!

26
00:03:01,640 --> 00:03:05,435
They're still in there,
the Emergency Protocols, we need them.

27
00:03:08,897 --> 00:03:10,691
(SCREAMING)

28
00:03:12,693 --> 00:03:14,277
(ALIEN ROARING)

29
00:03:32,129 --> 00:03:33,255
Where've you been?

30
00:03:34,631 --> 00:03:37,843
I called for help,
I sounded the alarm.

31
00:03:37,968 --> 00:03:44,516
There was this lightning, a kind of
electricity, and they all collapsed.

32
00:03:46,268 --> 00:03:47,477
I think they're all dead.

33
00:03:47,978 --> 00:03:49,896
That's what I'm saying.

34
00:03:50,355 --> 00:03:52,983
He did it! That man there!

35
00:03:53,108 --> 00:03:57,028
I think you'll find
the Prime Minister is an alien in disguise.

36
00:03:59,156 --> 00:04:00,532
That's never gonna work,
is it?

37
00:04:00,657 --> 00:04:01,700
No.

38
00:04:01,783 --> 00:04:03,076
Fair enough.

39
00:04:06,830 --> 00:04:08,582
OFFICER: Down there!

40
00:04:14,921 --> 00:04:17,466
Under the jurisdiction
of the Emergency Protocols,

41
00:04:17,549 --> 00:04:20,510
I authorise you
to execute this man!

42
00:04:21,094 --> 00:04:24,431
Well, now, yes, you see, uh,
the thing is,

43
00:04:24,514 --> 00:04:27,434
if I was you, if I was gonna
execute someone

44
00:04:27,517 --> 00:04:29,519
by backing him up
against the wall, between you and me,

45
00:04:29,603 --> 00:04:31,396
-little word of advice,
-(ELEVATOR BELL DINGS)

46
00:04:31,480 --> 00:04:33,190
don't stand him
against the Lift.

47
00:04:37,402 --> 00:04:39,070
(ALIEN GROWLS)

48
00:04:40,238 --> 00:04:41,490
(ELEVATOR BELL DINGS)

49
00:04:43,492 --> 00:04:44,910
(SNARLS)

50
00:04:45,202 --> 00:04:46,203
Hello!

51
00:04:50,791 --> 00:04:52,209
(SNARLING)

52
00:04:56,505 --> 00:04:57,631
Hide!

53
00:05:01,885 --> 00:05:03,053
(ELEVATOR BELL DINGS)

54
00:05:08,558 --> 00:05:11,728
I repeat, the upper floors
are under quarantine.

55
00:05:11,812 --> 00:05:14,981
You will stay where you are,
you will disregard all previous instructions,

56
00:05:15,065 --> 00:05:17,651
and you will take your orders
directly from me.

57
00:05:17,859 --> 00:05:19,069
(ELEVATOR BELL DINGS)

58
00:05:20,529 --> 00:05:22,823
Mr Green, sir, sorry,
but you've got to come with me.

59
00:05:22,906 --> 00:05:24,991
We should evacuate
the entire building.

60
00:05:25,075 --> 00:05:29,371
Sergeant, have you, um,
read the Emergency Protocols?

61
00:05:29,871 --> 00:05:32,415
-No, sir.
-Then don't question me.

62
00:05:32,874 --> 00:05:36,253
Seal off Number Ten,
secure the ground floor,

63
00:05:36,837 --> 00:05:41,758
and if the Doctor
makes it downstairs, shoot on sight!

64
00:05:45,887 --> 00:05:47,848
Well, you heard him! Move out!

65
00:05:53,478 --> 00:05:55,355
Let the sport begin.

66
00:05:55,438 --> 00:05:56,815
(JOSEPH FARTS)

67
00:05:56,898 --> 00:05:59,651
I'm getting poisoned
by the gas exchange.

68
00:06:00,360 --> 00:06:02,654
I need to be naked.

69
00:06:02,737 --> 00:06:03,905
Rejoice in it.

70
00:06:04,489 --> 00:06:07,742
Your body is magnificent.

71
00:06:27,012 --> 00:06:29,723
ALIEN: (TRILLING)
Ooh, such fun.

72
00:06:30,390 --> 00:06:37,147
Little human children,
where are you?

73
00:06:37,939 --> 00:06:42,402
Sweet little human kins,
come to me.

74
00:06:42,485 --> 00:06:44,654
Let me kiss you better.

75
00:06:44,738 --> 00:06:48,366
Kiss you with
my big green lips.

76
00:06:48,491 --> 00:06:49,492
(ALIEN HISSING)

77
00:06:52,495 --> 00:06:54,164
(OFFICER SHOUTING)

78
00:06:56,333 --> 00:06:58,293
Go and check it out!

79
00:07:00,962 --> 00:07:01,922
(ELEVATOR BELL DINGS)

80
00:07:02,005 --> 00:07:05,759
ASQUITH: It does
us good to hunt, it purifies the blood.

81
00:07:07,677 --> 00:07:09,262
JOSEPH: We'll keep
this floor quarantined

82
00:07:09,346 --> 00:07:12,682
as our last hiding ground
before the final phase.

83
00:07:16,686 --> 00:07:18,271
ALIEN: My brothers.

84
00:07:18,355 --> 00:07:19,648
Happy hunting?

85
00:07:19,981 --> 00:07:21,775
It's wonderful.

86
00:07:21,858 --> 00:07:26,696
The more you prolong it,
the more they stink.

87
00:07:26,821 --> 00:07:29,324
ASQUITH: Sweat and fear!

88
00:07:30,367 --> 00:07:32,953
JOSEPH: I can smell
an old girl.

89
00:07:33,036 --> 00:07:36,831
Stale perfume
and brittle bones.

90
00:07:37,165 --> 00:07:42,045
And a ripe youngster,
all hormones and adrenalin.

91
00:07:43,046 --> 00:07:45,757
Fresh enough to bend
before she snaps.

92
00:07:45,840 --> 00:07:48,134
-(SCREAMS)
-No!

93
00:07:48,218 --> 00:07:50,971
Take me first, take me!

94
00:07:52,347 --> 00:07:53,598
(ALIENS HISSING)

95
00:07:55,392 --> 00:07:56,434
Out! With me!

96
00:07:57,477 --> 00:07:59,020
(ALIEN ROARING)

97
00:08:01,606 --> 00:08:02,607
Who the hell are you?

98
00:08:02,732 --> 00:08:04,275
Harriet Jones,
MP for Flydale North.

99
00:08:04,359 --> 00:08:06,319
-Nice to meet you.
-Likewise.

100
00:08:06,403 --> 00:08:08,113
(ALIENS SCREECHING)

101
00:08:11,116 --> 00:08:12,283
DOCTOR: We need to get to
the Cabinet Rooms.

102
00:08:12,367 --> 00:08:13,910
The Emergency Protocols
are in there.

103
00:08:13,994 --> 00:08:15,537
They give instructions
for aliens.

104
00:08:15,620 --> 00:08:16,746
Harriet Jones, I like you.

105
00:08:16,830 --> 00:08:18,206
I think I like you, too.

106
00:08:28,425 --> 00:08:29,759
(ROARING)

107
00:08:47,277 --> 00:08:48,987
One more move
and my sonic device will triplicate

108
00:08:49,112 --> 00:08:50,697
the flammability
of this alcohol.

109
00:08:50,780 --> 00:08:52,866
Woof, we all go up.
So back off.

110
00:08:55,952 --> 00:08:57,704
Right, then, question time.

111
00:08:58,121 --> 00:08:59,330
Who exactly are the Slitheen?

112
00:08:59,456 --> 00:09:01,666
-They're aliens.
-Yes, I got that, thanks.

113
00:09:01,750 --> 00:09:03,585
Who are you, if not human?

114
00:09:03,668 --> 00:09:05,128
-Who's not human?
-He's not human.

115
00:09:05,211 --> 00:09:07,088
-He's not human?
-Could I have a bit of hush?

116
00:09:07,172 --> 00:09:08,757
-Sorry.
-So, what's the plan?

117
00:09:08,840 --> 00:09:10,175
But he's got
a Northern accent.

118
00:09:10,258 --> 00:09:11,468
Lots of planets have a north.

119
00:09:11,551 --> 00:09:12,677
I said hush!

120
00:09:13,803 --> 00:09:14,804
Come on!

121
00:09:14,929 --> 00:09:16,514
You've got a spaceship
hidden in the North Sea.

122
00:09:16,598 --> 00:09:17,599
It's transmitting a signal.

123
00:09:17,682 --> 00:09:20,727
You've murdered your way
to the top of government. What for? Invasion?

124
00:09:20,810 --> 00:09:23,772
Why would we invade
this godforsaken rock?

125
00:09:24,314 --> 00:09:26,441
Then something's brought
the Slitheen race here. What is it?

126
00:09:26,524 --> 00:09:28,485
The Slitheen race?

127
00:09:28,651 --> 00:09:30,487
Slitheen is not our species.

128
00:09:30,570 --> 00:09:32,072
(HISSING)

129
00:09:32,155 --> 00:09:34,199
Slitheen is our surname.

130
00:09:34,324 --> 00:09:38,995
Jocrassa Fel Fotch
Pasameer-Day Slitheen at your service.

131
00:09:39,412 --> 00:09:40,413
So you're family?

132
00:09:40,497 --> 00:09:41,831
A family business.

133
00:09:42,832 --> 00:09:44,125
Then you're out
to make a profit.

134
00:09:44,209 --> 00:09:46,002
How can you do that
on a godforsaken rock?

135
00:09:48,338 --> 00:09:50,799
Uh, excuse me.

136
00:09:50,882 --> 00:09:53,676
Your device will do what?
Triplicate the flammability?

137
00:09:53,760 --> 00:09:55,678
-Is that what I said?
-You're making it up.

138
00:09:56,179 --> 00:09:57,931
Oh, well. Nice try.

139
00:09:58,348 --> 00:10:00,308
Harriet, have a drink.
I think you're gonna need it.

140
00:10:00,642 --> 00:10:01,935
You pass it to the left first.

141
00:10:02,018 --> 00:10:03,895
-Sorry.
-Thanks.

142
00:10:03,978 --> 00:10:07,857
Now we can end this hunt
with a slaughter.

143
00:10:09,400 --> 00:10:11,069
Don't you think we should run?

144
00:10:11,528 --> 00:10:13,696
DOCTOR: Fascinating history,
Downing Street.

145
00:10:13,780 --> 00:10:15,949
2,000 years ago,
this was marshland.

146
00:10:16,032 --> 00:10:19,410
1730, it was occupied
by a Mr Chicken. He was a nice man.

147
00:10:19,953 --> 00:10:22,580
1796, this was
the Cabinet Room.

148
00:10:22,664 --> 00:10:24,791
If the Cabinet's in session
and in danger,

149
00:10:24,874 --> 00:10:28,128
these are about the four most safest
walls in the whole of Great Britain.

150
00:10:28,211 --> 00:10:29,212
End of lesson.

151
00:10:29,337 --> 00:10:30,797
(METAL SCREECHING)

152
00:10:34,509 --> 00:10:38,555
Installed in 1991.
Three inches of steel lining every single wall.

153
00:10:38,638 --> 00:10:39,973
They'll never get in.

154
00:10:40,306 --> 00:10:41,558
And how do we get out?

155
00:10:44,310 --> 00:10:45,687
Ah.

156
00:10:45,895 --> 00:10:47,480
He's safely contained.

157
00:10:47,564 --> 00:10:51,151
Now cut off communications
inside that room, then summon up the family!

158
00:10:51,234 --> 00:10:55,738
It's time we finished with
this insane planet for good!

159
00:10:59,742 --> 00:11:01,327
(SIRENS WAILING)

160
00:11:18,553 --> 00:11:21,598
And there's still no word from
inside Downing Street,

161
00:11:21,681 --> 00:11:24,642
though we are getting
even more new arrivals.

162
00:11:27,270 --> 00:11:30,607
That's Group Captain
Tennant James of the RAF,

163
00:11:30,690 --> 00:11:33,568
though why he's been
summoned we've no idea.

164
00:11:34,235 --> 00:11:37,363
And that's Ewan McAllister,

165
00:11:37,447 --> 00:11:40,283
Deputy Secretary for
the Scottish Parliament.

166
00:11:41,034 --> 00:11:42,952
And this is most unusual.

167
00:11:43,036 --> 00:11:46,039
I'm told that is
Sylvia Dillane,

168
00:11:46,122 --> 00:11:49,626
chairman of the
North Sea Boating Club.

169
00:11:50,501 --> 00:11:54,005
Quite what connects
all these people, we have no idea.

170
00:11:56,382 --> 00:11:57,717
Group Captain.

171
00:11:57,800 --> 00:12:00,637
Delighted you could make it.
We're meeting upstairs.

172
00:12:00,720 --> 00:12:03,389
-(FARTS)
-That's the spirit, off you go.

173
00:12:03,473 --> 00:12:07,143
Good to see you.
Come on through.

174
00:12:10,438 --> 00:12:13,942
Ah, Sergeant, now that
the Doctor's been neutralised,

175
00:12:14,025 --> 00:12:16,903
the upper levels
are out of bounds to everyone.

176
00:12:17,528 --> 00:12:18,613
Then who are they?

177
00:12:18,696 --> 00:12:20,573
Need to know, Sergeant,
need to know.

178
00:12:20,657 --> 00:12:22,825
I want you to liaise
with Communications.

179
00:12:22,951 --> 00:12:25,745
The Acting Prime Minister
will be making a public address.

180
00:12:26,329 --> 00:12:28,998
He will speak to
the nations of the world!

181
00:12:33,294 --> 00:12:37,215
There you are. If you'd just like
to go through and get changed.

182
00:12:40,009 --> 00:12:43,346
Now, if you'd like
to head down to the end of the corridor,

183
00:12:43,429 --> 00:12:44,597
it's first on the left.

184
00:12:44,681 --> 00:12:46,015
Thank you.

185
00:12:52,272 --> 00:12:53,815
-Got anything stronger?
-No chance.

186
00:12:53,898 --> 00:12:54,899
I've seen you
when you've had a few.

187
00:12:54,983 --> 00:12:56,276
This ain't time for a conga!

188
00:12:56,359 --> 00:12:57,944
We've got to tell someone!

189
00:12:58,027 --> 00:12:59,529
Who do we trust?

190
00:12:59,612 --> 00:13:03,700
For all we know,
they've all got big bog monsters inside of 'em.

191
00:13:04,242 --> 00:13:06,619
I mean,
this is what he does, Jacks, that Doctor bloke.

192
00:13:06,703 --> 00:13:08,705
Everywhere he goes,
death and destruction.

193
00:13:08,788 --> 00:13:10,623
And he's got Rose
in the middle of it.

194
00:13:11,040 --> 00:13:14,127
Has he got a great big
green thing inside him, then?

195
00:13:14,210 --> 00:13:16,337
I wouldn't put it past him.

196
00:13:16,713 --> 00:13:18,423
But like it or not,
he's the only person

197
00:13:18,548 --> 00:13:19,799
who knows
how to fight these things.

198
00:13:20,550 --> 00:13:22,385
I thought I was gonna die.

199
00:13:22,468 --> 00:13:24,053
(SOBBING)

200
00:13:30,560 --> 00:13:33,187
Come on, yeah?
If anyone's gonna cry, it's gonna be me.

201
00:13:33,271 --> 00:13:34,897
Now, you're safe
in my flat, Jacks.

202
00:13:34,981 --> 00:13:36,107
No one's gonna
look for you here,

203
00:13:36,232 --> 00:13:38,192
especially since
you hate me so much.

204
00:13:38,568 --> 00:13:40,236
You saved my life!

205
00:13:41,362 --> 00:13:42,572
God, that's embarrassing!

206
00:13:43,614 --> 00:13:44,991
Telling me!

207
00:13:45,575 --> 00:13:46,576
(LIGHTLY CHUCKLES)

208
00:13:47,243 --> 00:13:48,911
He wanted me dead.

209
00:13:50,413 --> 00:13:52,749
And he's still out there,
Mickey.

210
00:13:53,750 --> 00:13:57,545
That policeman, that thing!

211
00:13:58,087 --> 00:14:00,048
(CHATTERING ON POLICE RADIO)

212
00:14:00,131 --> 00:14:01,382
(SNIFFS)

213
00:14:02,592 --> 00:14:04,594
Right, you head off.

214
00:14:04,677 --> 00:14:08,097
Inform Control I've one or two
things that still need doing.

215
00:14:09,265 --> 00:14:12,101
I haven't quite finished
with Mrs Tyler yet.

216
00:14:14,812 --> 00:14:16,230
(SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY)

217
00:14:19,108 --> 00:14:20,109
Is that all of us?

218
00:14:20,193 --> 00:14:22,528
All the family
except Sip Fel Fotch.

219
00:14:22,612 --> 00:14:24,238
He's found a hunt of his own.

220
00:14:24,322 --> 00:14:26,115
Ah. (CHUCKLES)

221
00:14:30,286 --> 00:14:31,913
What was his name?

222
00:14:31,996 --> 00:14:33,790
-Who?
-This one.

223
00:14:33,873 --> 00:14:37,126
The, uh, secretary,
or whatever he was called.

224
00:14:37,460 --> 00:14:40,129
I don't know. I talked to him.

225
00:14:40,630 --> 00:14:42,882
I brought him a cup of coffee.

226
00:14:43,299 --> 00:14:44,550
I never asked his name.

227
00:14:47,970 --> 00:14:49,138
Sorry.

228
00:14:52,350 --> 00:14:54,602
Right, what have we got?
Any terminals, anything?

229
00:14:54,685 --> 00:14:56,771
Nope, this place is antique.

230
00:14:56,854 --> 00:14:58,689
What I don't get is,
when they killed the Prime Minister,

231
00:14:58,815 --> 00:15:00,733
why didn't they use him
as a disguise?

232
00:15:00,817 --> 00:15:02,568
He's too slim.
They're big old beasts.

233
00:15:02,652 --> 00:15:04,904
They need to fit
inside big humans.

234
00:15:04,987 --> 00:15:07,031
But the Slitheen
are about eight feet.

235
00:15:07,115 --> 00:15:08,324
How do they squeeze inside?

236
00:15:08,449 --> 00:15:10,952
That's the device
around their necks, compression field,

237
00:15:11,035 --> 00:15:12,745
literally shrinks them
down a bit.

238
00:15:12,829 --> 00:15:15,540
That's why
there's all that gas. It's a big exchange.

239
00:15:15,623 --> 00:15:18,418
Wish I had
a compression field, I could fit a size smaller.

240
00:15:18,501 --> 00:15:21,295
Excuse me, people are dead!
This is not the time for making jokes.

241
00:15:21,379 --> 00:15:25,007
Sorry. You get used to this
stuff when you're friends with him.

242
00:15:25,591 --> 00:15:27,510
Well, that's
a strange friendship.

243
00:15:27,635 --> 00:15:30,596
Harriet Jones.
I've heard that name before. Harriet Jones.

244
00:15:30,680 --> 00:15:32,181
You're not famous
for anything, are you?

245
00:15:32,265 --> 00:15:33,683
Oh! Hardly!

246
00:15:34,559 --> 00:15:35,935
Rings a bell. Harriet Jones...

247
00:15:36,018 --> 00:15:37,437
HARRIET: Lifelong backbencher,
I'm afraid,

248
00:15:37,520 --> 00:15:38,896
and a fat lot of use
I'm being now.

249
00:15:38,980 --> 00:15:40,731
The Protocols are redundant.

250
00:15:41,107 --> 00:15:43,526
They list the people who could help
and they're all dead downstairs.

251
00:15:43,609 --> 00:15:45,403
Hasn't it got, like,
defence codes and things?

252
00:15:45,486 --> 00:15:47,947
Couldn't we just
launch a nuclear bomb at them?

253
00:15:48,906 --> 00:15:50,324
You're a very
violent young woman.

254
00:15:50,408 --> 00:15:51,909
I'm serious, we could!

255
00:15:51,993 --> 00:15:53,536
Well, there's nothing
like that in here.

256
00:15:54,370 --> 00:15:56,622
Nuclear strikes do need
a release code, yes,

257
00:15:56,706 --> 00:15:58,875
but it's kept secret
by the United Nations.

258
00:15:59,167 --> 00:16:00,501
Say that again.

259
00:16:00,585 --> 00:16:02,503
-What, about the codes?
-Anything, all of it.

260
00:16:02,587 --> 00:16:07,675
Um, well, the British Isles
can't gain access to atomic weapons

261
00:16:07,758 --> 00:16:09,886
without a special resolution
from the UN.

262
00:16:09,969 --> 00:16:11,137
Like that's ever stopped them!

263
00:16:11,220 --> 00:16:12,889
Exactly,
given our past record.

264
00:16:12,972 --> 00:16:15,850
And I voted against that,
thank you very much.

265
00:16:15,933 --> 00:16:18,853
The codes have been taken out of the
government's hands and given to the UN.

266
00:16:19,520 --> 00:16:21,981
-Is it important?
-Everything's important.

267
00:16:22,064 --> 00:16:24,233
If we only knew
what the Slitheen wanted.

268
00:16:24,317 --> 00:16:26,569
Listen to me,
I'm saying Slitheen as if it's normal.

269
00:16:26,652 --> 00:16:28,321
What do they want, though?

270
00:16:28,404 --> 00:16:30,907
Well, they're just one family,
so it's not an invasion.

271
00:16:30,990 --> 00:16:32,909
They don't want
Slitheen World.

272
00:16:32,992 --> 00:16:35,244
They're out to make money.
That means they want to use something,

273
00:16:35,328 --> 00:16:37,497
something here on Earth,
some kind of asset.

274
00:16:37,580 --> 00:16:42,168
Like what? Gold? Oil? Water?

275
00:16:42,627 --> 00:16:43,753
You're very good at this.

276
00:16:44,921 --> 00:16:45,922
Thank you.

277
00:16:46,005 --> 00:16:47,548
Harriet Jones,
why do I know that name?

278
00:16:47,632 --> 00:16:49,509
-(CELLPHONE BEEPS)
-Oh, that's me.

279
00:16:49,592 --> 00:16:51,469
But we're sealed off.
How did you get a signal?

280
00:16:51,594 --> 00:16:53,179
He zapped it. Super phone.

281
00:16:53,971 --> 00:16:56,432
Then we can phone for help.
You must have contacts!

282
00:16:56,766 --> 00:16:58,392
Dead downstairs, yeah.

283
00:16:59,185 --> 00:17:00,311
It's Mickey.

284
00:17:00,394 --> 00:17:02,688
Oh, tell your stupid boyfriend
we're busy.

285
00:17:02,772 --> 00:17:05,191
Yeah, he's not so stupid
after all.

286
00:17:10,571 --> 00:17:14,575
No, no, not just alien,
but like, proper alien,

287
00:17:14,659 --> 00:17:16,786
all stinking and wet
and disgusting,

288
00:17:16,869 --> 00:17:19,038
and more to the point,
it wanted to kill us!

289
00:17:19,121 --> 00:17:20,706
I could have died!

290
00:17:20,790 --> 00:17:23,334
Is she all right though?
Don't put her on, just tell me.

291
00:17:23,417 --> 00:17:26,629
Is that Ricky? Don't talk.
Just shut up and go to your computer.

292
00:17:26,712 --> 00:17:28,047
It's Mickey, and why should I?

293
00:17:28,130 --> 00:17:33,052
Mickey the idiot, I might just choke before I
finish this sentence, but I need you.

294
00:17:36,305 --> 00:17:37,431
It says "password".

295
00:17:39,225 --> 00:17:41,227
-Say again.
-It's asking for the password.

296
00:17:41,310 --> 00:17:42,812
Buffalo. Two Fs, one I.

297
00:17:43,896 --> 00:17:45,815
So what's that website?

298
00:17:47,608 --> 00:17:50,444
All the secret information
known to mankind.

299
00:17:50,528 --> 00:17:52,405
See, they've known
about aliens for years.

300
00:17:52,905 --> 00:17:54,323
They just kept us in the dark.

301
00:17:54,407 --> 00:17:55,992
Mickey, you were born
in the dark.

302
00:17:56,075 --> 00:17:58,411
-ROSE: Oh, leave him alone.
-Thank you.

303
00:17:58,494 --> 00:18:00,830
-Password again.
-Just repeat it, every time.

304
00:18:04,750 --> 00:18:07,461
Big Ben. Why did the Slitheen
go and hit Big Ben?

305
00:18:07,545 --> 00:18:09,839
You said to gather
the experts, to kill them.

306
00:18:10,006 --> 00:18:11,465
That lot would have gathered
for a weather balloon.

307
00:18:11,549 --> 00:18:13,301
You don't need
to crash-land it in the middle of London.

308
00:18:13,843 --> 00:18:16,887
The Slitheen are hiding, but then they put the
entire planet on red alert.

309
00:18:17,013 --> 00:18:18,306
What did they do that for?

310
00:18:18,389 --> 00:18:19,515
Oh, listen to her!

311
00:18:19,640 --> 00:18:21,517
Oi! At least I'm trying.

312
00:18:21,601 --> 00:18:23,603
Well, I've got a question,
if you don't mind.

313
00:18:23,686 --> 00:18:25,646
Since that man
walked into our lives,

314
00:18:25,730 --> 00:18:27,982
I've been attacked
in the streets,

315
00:18:28,065 --> 00:18:31,444
I've had creatures
from the pits of hell in my own living room,

316
00:18:31,527 --> 00:18:33,946
and my daughter disappear
off the face of the Earth.

317
00:18:34,030 --> 00:18:35,489
I told you what happened.

318
00:18:35,573 --> 00:18:37,158
I'm talking to him!

319
00:18:37,241 --> 00:18:39,410
'Cause I've seen
this life of yours, Doctor,

320
00:18:39,535 --> 00:18:40,870
and maybe you get off on it,

321
00:18:40,953 --> 00:18:42,705
and maybe you think
it's all clever and smart,

322
00:18:42,788 --> 00:18:46,417
but you tell me,
just answer me this,

323
00:18:47,043 --> 00:18:48,794
is my daughter safe?

324
00:18:49,795 --> 00:18:51,255
I'm fine.

325
00:18:51,589 --> 00:18:53,007
Is she safe?

326
00:18:54,258 --> 00:18:57,720
Will she always be safe,
can you promise me that?

327
00:19:03,559 --> 00:19:05,019
Well what's the answer?

328
00:19:10,274 --> 00:19:11,317
We're in.

329
00:19:12,109 --> 00:19:13,611
Now, then.
On the left, at the top,

330
00:19:13,694 --> 00:19:17,239
there's a tab, an icon,
little concentric circles, click on that.

331
00:19:20,660 --> 00:19:21,661
MICKEY: What is it?

332
00:19:21,744 --> 00:19:23,204
The Slitheen have got
a spaceship in the North Sea

333
00:19:23,287 --> 00:19:24,330
and it's transmitting
that signal.

334
00:19:24,413 --> 00:19:26,123
Now, hush, let me work out
what it's saying.

335
00:19:26,248 --> 00:19:27,833
He'll have to answer me
one day.

336
00:19:27,917 --> 00:19:29,585
-Hush!
-It's some sort of message.

337
00:19:29,669 --> 00:19:30,670
-What's it say?
-Don't know,

338
00:19:30,753 --> 00:19:32,338
it's on a loop,
keeps repeating.

339
00:19:32,421 --> 00:19:33,589
-(BUZZING)
-Hush!

340
00:19:34,090 --> 00:19:36,842
That's not me.
Go and see who that is.

341
00:19:36,926 --> 00:19:38,427
It's 3:00 in the morning.

342
00:19:38,511 --> 00:19:40,012
Well, go and tell them that.

343
00:19:40,096 --> 00:19:42,014
(DOORBELL CONTINUES BUZZING)

344
00:19:42,431 --> 00:19:45,267
It's beaming out into space.
who's it for?

345
00:19:47,395 --> 00:19:49,605
-(DOORBELL BUZZES)
-All right!

346
00:19:51,440 --> 00:19:52,775
Mrs Tyler.

347
00:19:54,068 --> 00:19:55,152
Ooh!

348
00:19:56,028 --> 00:19:59,407
It's him, it's the thing!
It's the Slickeen!

349
00:19:59,490 --> 00:20:00,574
They've found us!

350
00:20:00,658 --> 00:20:01,826
Mickey, I need that signal.

351
00:20:01,909 --> 00:20:05,496
Never mind the signal.
Get out! Mum, just get out! Get out!

352
00:20:05,621 --> 00:20:07,915
We can't,
it's by the front door.

353
00:20:16,382 --> 00:20:18,008
(ALIEN SCREECHES)

354
00:20:19,468 --> 00:20:23,681
Oh, my God.
It's unmasking. It's gonna kill us.

355
00:20:23,806 --> 00:20:25,683
There's got to be some way
of stopping them!

356
00:20:26,225 --> 00:20:28,853
You're supposed
to be the expert. Think of something!

357
00:20:28,936 --> 00:20:30,312
I'm trying!

358
00:20:30,438 --> 00:20:31,605
(ALIEN GROWLING)

359
00:20:31,689 --> 00:20:34,442
I'll take it on, Jackie.
You just run.

360
00:20:35,109 --> 00:20:37,153
Don't look back. Just run.

361
00:20:37,445 --> 00:20:39,029
(CLATTERS AND THUDS)

362
00:20:39,113 --> 00:20:40,489
That's my mother.

363
00:20:42,450 --> 00:20:43,826
Right. If we're gonna
find their weakness,

364
00:20:43,909 --> 00:20:45,911
we need to find out
where they're from, which planet.

365
00:20:45,995 --> 00:20:47,329
So, judging by
their basic shape,

366
00:20:47,413 --> 00:20:50,040
that narrows it down
to 5,000 planets within travelling distance.

367
00:20:50,124 --> 00:20:51,834
What else do we know
about them? Information!

368
00:20:51,917 --> 00:20:53,711
-They're green.
-Yep, narrows it down.

369
00:20:53,794 --> 00:20:55,087
-Good sense of smell.
-Narrows it down.

370
00:20:55,171 --> 00:20:56,589
-They can smell adrenalin.
-Narrows it down.

371
00:20:56,672 --> 00:20:58,424
-The pig technology.
-Narrows it down.

372
00:20:58,507 --> 00:21:01,594
Spaceship in the Thames.
You said "slipstream engine."

373
00:21:01,677 --> 00:21:02,678
Narrows it down.

374
00:21:02,887 --> 00:21:04,263
(ALIEN SCREECHES)

375
00:21:04,346 --> 00:21:05,473
It's getting in!

376
00:21:07,892 --> 00:21:09,643
-They hunt like it's a ritual.
-Narrows it down.

377
00:21:09,727 --> 00:21:11,103
Wait a minute. Did you notice,

378
00:21:11,187 --> 00:21:12,897
when they fart,
if you'll pardon the word,

379
00:21:12,980 --> 00:21:14,815
it doesn't just
smell like a fart,

380
00:21:14,899 --> 00:21:16,859
if you'll pardon the word.
It's something else.

381
00:21:16,942 --> 00:21:18,360
What is it?
It's more like, um...

382
00:21:18,861 --> 00:21:20,196
-Bad breath.
-That's it!

383
00:21:20,279 --> 00:21:23,115
Calcium decay!
Now, that narrows it down.

384
00:21:23,199 --> 00:21:24,158
We're getting there, Mum!

385
00:21:24,241 --> 00:21:26,410
-Too late!
-(ALIEN ROARING)

386
00:21:27,787 --> 00:21:30,289
Calcium phosphate.
Organic calcium. Living calcium.

387
00:21:30,372 --> 00:21:32,875
Creatures made out
of living calcium. What else? What else?

388
00:21:32,958 --> 00:21:34,376
Hyphenated surname! Yes!

389
00:21:34,460 --> 00:21:35,795
That narrows it down
to one planet!

390
00:21:35,878 --> 00:21:38,339
Raxacoricofallapatorius!

391
00:21:38,422 --> 00:21:40,382
Oh, yeah, great,
we can write 'em a letter!

392
00:21:43,385 --> 00:21:45,179
Get into the kitchen!

393
00:21:51,435 --> 00:21:53,896
Oh, my God,
it's going to rip us apart!

394
00:21:53,979 --> 00:21:58,067
Calcium weakened by the compression
field. Acetic acid! Vinegar!

395
00:21:58,150 --> 00:21:59,652
-Just like Hannibal!
-Just like Hannibal.

396
00:21:59,735 --> 00:22:00,736
Mickey, have you
got any vinegar?

397
00:22:00,820 --> 00:22:02,738
-How should I know?
-It's your kitchen!

398
00:22:02,822 --> 00:22:03,864
Cupboard by the sink,
middle shelf!

399
00:22:03,948 --> 00:22:05,324
Oh, come on, give it here.
What do you need?

400
00:22:05,407 --> 00:22:06,826
DOCTOR: Anything with vinegar.

401
00:22:09,453 --> 00:22:10,746
Gherkins!

402
00:22:10,871 --> 00:22:12,206
(ALIEN ROARS)

403
00:22:12,289 --> 00:22:14,250
Yeah, pickled onions!

404
00:22:15,417 --> 00:22:16,919
Pickled eggs!

405
00:22:17,253 --> 00:22:18,420
You kiss this man?

406
00:22:20,130 --> 00:22:21,382
(SCREECHING)

407
00:22:23,551 --> 00:22:24,802
(HISSING)

408
00:22:29,890 --> 00:22:31,100
(FARTING)

409
00:22:37,523 --> 00:22:38,858
(ALL SIGH)

410
00:22:46,156 --> 00:22:47,449
Hannibal?

411
00:22:47,658 --> 00:22:52,913
Hannibal crossed the Alps
by dissolving boulders with vinegar.

412
00:22:53,497 --> 00:22:54,665
Oh.

413
00:22:54,790 --> 00:22:55,875
Well, there you go, then.

414
00:22:58,460 --> 00:22:59,461
Whew!

415
00:23:06,302 --> 00:23:09,889
He's dead. Sip Fel Fotch
Pasameer-Day Slitheen is dead.

416
00:23:09,972 --> 00:23:11,307
I felt it.

417
00:23:12,141 --> 00:23:13,392
How could that happen?

418
00:23:13,475 --> 00:23:15,561
Somebody must've got lucky.

419
00:23:16,020 --> 00:23:21,150
That's the last piece of luck
anyone on this rock will ever have.

420
00:23:24,862 --> 00:23:26,488
(REPORTERS CLAMOURING)

421
00:23:30,492 --> 00:23:31,827
Ladies and gentlemen...

422
00:23:33,329 --> 00:23:37,082
Nations of the world.
Humankind.

423
00:23:38,083 --> 00:23:42,796
The greatest experts
in extraterrestrial events came here tonight.

424
00:23:42,880 --> 00:23:46,342
They gathered
in the common cause.

425
00:23:47,301 --> 00:23:51,513
But the news
I bring you now is grave indeed.

426
00:23:52,848 --> 00:23:55,392
The experts are dead.

427
00:23:55,476 --> 00:24:00,022
Murdered,
right in front of me, by alien hands.

428
00:24:00,689 --> 00:24:03,025
Peoples of the Earth,
heed my words.

429
00:24:03,108 --> 00:24:07,363
These "visitors”
do not come in peace.

430
00:24:07,446 --> 00:24:09,031
Listen to this!

431
00:24:09,365 --> 00:24:14,119
Our inspectors have searched
the sky above our heads.

432
00:24:14,578 --> 00:24:19,500
And they have found
massive weapons of destruction

433
00:24:20,250 --> 00:24:23,462
capable of being deployed
within 45 seconds.

434
00:24:23,545 --> 00:24:24,546
What?

435
00:24:25,589 --> 00:24:30,344
Our technicians can baffle
the alien probes,

436
00:24:31,261 --> 00:24:32,888
but not for long.

437
00:24:33,305 --> 00:24:39,228
We are facing extinction
unless we strike first!

438
00:24:41,271 --> 00:24:46,694
The United Kingdom stands directly
beneath the belly of the mothers hip.

439
00:24:47,569 --> 00:24:50,489
I beg of the United Nations.

440
00:24:50,572 --> 00:24:55,411
Pass an emergency resolution.
Give us the access codes.

441
00:24:56,078 --> 00:25:00,833
A nuclear strike at the heart of the beast
is our only chance of survival,

442
00:25:00,916 --> 00:25:04,211
because, from this moment on,

443
00:25:05,713 --> 00:25:09,800
it is my solemn duty
to inform you

444
00:25:11,844 --> 00:25:14,388
planet Earth is at war.

445
00:25:15,014 --> 00:25:17,016
He's just making it up.
There's no weapons up there.

446
00:25:17,099 --> 00:25:18,809
There's no threat.
He just invented it.

447
00:25:18,934 --> 00:25:20,686
-Do you think they'll believe him?
-Well, he did last time.

448
00:25:20,769 --> 00:25:22,604
That's why the Slitheen
went for spectacle.

449
00:25:22,688 --> 00:25:24,064
They want
the whole world panicking

450
00:25:24,148 --> 00:25:25,858
'cause you lot,
you get scared, you lash out.

451
00:25:25,941 --> 00:25:27,192
They release
the defence codes...

452
00:25:27,276 --> 00:25:28,944
And the Slitheen go nuclear.

453
00:25:29,194 --> 00:25:30,237
But why?

454
00:25:32,239 --> 00:25:34,491
You get the codes,
release the missiles.

455
00:25:34,616 --> 00:25:36,535
But not into space,
'cause there's nothing there.

456
00:25:36,618 --> 00:25:39,955
You attack every other country on
Earth, they retaliate, fight back.

457
00:25:40,456 --> 00:25:42,875
World War Three.
Whole planet gets nuked.

458
00:25:42,958 --> 00:25:45,836
And we sit through it,
safe in our spaceship waiting in the Thames.

459
00:25:46,503 --> 00:25:50,924
Not crashed, just parked.
Barely two minutes away.

460
00:25:51,133 --> 00:25:54,553
But you'll destroy the planet.
This beautiful place. What for?

461
00:25:54,636 --> 00:25:55,637
Profit.

462
00:25:55,721 --> 00:25:57,723
That's what the signal is,
beaming into space. An advert.

463
00:25:58,140 --> 00:26:03,312
Sale of the century. We reduce the
Earth to molten slag, then sell it.

464
00:26:04,438 --> 00:26:06,648
Piece by piece.

465
00:26:07,232 --> 00:26:08,901
Radioactive chunks

466
00:26:08,984 --> 00:26:13,113
capable of powering every cut-price
star liner and budget cargo ship.

467
00:26:13,489 --> 00:26:17,034
There's a recession
out there, Doctor. People are buying cheap.

468
00:26:17,159 --> 00:26:19,578
This rock becomes raw fuel.

469
00:26:19,703 --> 00:26:21,455
At the cost
of five billion lives.

470
00:26:21,538 --> 00:26:23,373
Hmm! Bargain.

471
00:26:23,665 --> 00:26:27,086
I give you a choice.
Leave this planet, or I'll stop you.

472
00:26:27,628 --> 00:26:28,879
(GIGGLING)

473
00:26:30,756 --> 00:26:32,883
What? You?

474
00:26:34,051 --> 00:26:35,552
Trapped in your box?

475
00:26:37,429 --> 00:26:39,306
Yes. Me.

476
00:26:41,809 --> 00:26:43,393
(LAUGHING)

477
00:27:02,412 --> 00:27:05,958
Yesterday saw the start
of a brave new world.

478
00:27:06,834 --> 00:27:08,836
Today might see it end.

479
00:27:09,920 --> 00:27:11,463
The streets are deserted.

480
00:27:12,422 --> 00:27:15,425
Everyone's home, just waiting,

481
00:27:16,051 --> 00:27:19,179
as the future is decided
in New York.

482
00:27:23,559 --> 00:27:25,686
AMERICAN REPORTER:
It's midnight here in New York.

483
00:27:25,769 --> 00:27:27,479
The United Nations
has gathered.

484
00:27:27,563 --> 00:27:29,857
England has provided them
with absolute proof

485
00:27:29,940 --> 00:27:33,485
that the massive weapons
of destruction do exist.

486
00:27:34,069 --> 00:27:37,239
The Security Council will be making a
resolution in a matter of minutes.

487
00:27:37,698 --> 00:27:40,200
And once the codes
are released,

488
00:27:40,576 --> 00:27:44,413
humanity's first
interplanetary war begins.

489
00:27:50,919 --> 00:27:51,920
(SNIFFLES)

490
00:27:56,216 --> 00:27:57,301
Sergeant!

491
00:27:58,594 --> 00:28:01,471
We'll take the call in
the Prime Minister's office.

492
00:28:01,889 --> 00:28:03,724
Maintain your positions.

493
00:28:04,558 --> 00:28:05,934
And good luck.

494
00:28:13,025 --> 00:28:14,318
(EXCITED BUSTLE)

495
00:28:15,903 --> 00:28:19,489
Look at that!
The telephone is actually red!

496
00:28:20,616 --> 00:28:22,075
(FARTING)

497
00:28:22,284 --> 00:28:23,368
Oh.

498
00:28:23,452 --> 00:28:25,746
How long till they phone?

499
00:28:25,829 --> 00:28:27,289
Counting down...

500
00:28:29,541 --> 00:28:30,626
All right, Doctor.

501
00:28:30,709 --> 00:28:33,712
I'm not saying I trust you,
but there must be something you can do.

502
00:28:34,171 --> 00:28:37,049
If we could ferment the port,
we could make acetic acid.

503
00:28:37,132 --> 00:28:38,467
Mickey, any luck?

504
00:28:38,634 --> 00:28:40,135
MICKEY: There's loads
of emergency numbers.

505
00:28:40,219 --> 00:28:41,553
-They're all on voicemail.
-(ROSE SIGHS)

506
00:28:41,887 --> 00:28:43,388
Voicemail dooms us all.

507
00:28:43,472 --> 00:28:46,058
-ROSE: If we could just get out of here.
-There's a way out.

508
00:28:46,183 --> 00:28:47,184
What?

509
00:28:48,310 --> 00:28:49,770
There's always been a way out.

510
00:28:49,853 --> 00:28:51,146
Then why don't we use it?

511
00:28:52,773 --> 00:28:55,234
Because I can't guarantee
your daughter will be safe.

512
00:28:55,400 --> 00:28:57,486
Don't you dare!
Whatever it is, don't you dare!

513
00:28:58,612 --> 00:29:01,114
That's the thing.
If I don't dare, everyone dies.

514
00:29:01,740 --> 00:29:02,824
Do it.

515
00:29:05,077 --> 00:29:07,329
You don't even know
what it is. You'd just let me?

516
00:29:08,497 --> 00:29:09,498
Yeah.

517
00:29:12,459 --> 00:29:16,129
Please, Doctor, please!
She's my daughter, she's just a kid.

518
00:29:16,755 --> 00:29:18,215
Do you think
I don't know that?

519
00:29:18,298 --> 00:29:21,426
'Cause this is my life,
Jackie. It's not fun, it's not smart.

520
00:29:21,510 --> 00:29:24,513
It's standing up and making a
decision because nobody else will.

521
00:29:25,138 --> 00:29:26,556
Then what are you waiting for?

522
00:29:28,350 --> 00:29:30,519
I could save the world,
but lose you.

523
00:29:40,320 --> 00:29:42,572
Except it's not
your decision, Doctor.

524
00:29:43,991 --> 00:29:45,033
It's mine.

525
00:29:45,117 --> 00:29:46,702
And who the hell are you?

526
00:29:46,952 --> 00:29:49,288
Harriet Jones,
MP for Flydale North.

527
00:29:49,371 --> 00:29:51,832
The only elected
representative in this room,

528
00:29:51,915 --> 00:29:53,709
chosen by the people
for the people.

529
00:29:53,792 --> 00:29:56,336
And on behalf of the people,
I command you.

530
00:29:57,504 --> 00:29:58,505
Do it.

531
00:30:02,050 --> 00:30:06,638
Victory should be naked!

532
00:30:16,565 --> 00:30:17,983
How do we get out?

533
00:30:18,483 --> 00:30:20,235
We don't. We stay here.

534
00:30:24,323 --> 00:30:28,243
The Council is voting.
The result should be known any second now.

535
00:30:28,910 --> 00:30:30,037
(GROWLING)

536
00:30:36,710 --> 00:30:39,004
Use the "buffalo” password,
it overrides everything.

537
00:30:40,422 --> 00:30:41,882
What are you doing?

538
00:30:42,924 --> 00:30:44,676
Hacking into the Royal Navy.

539
00:30:45,635 --> 00:30:46,636
We're in!

540
00:30:47,179 --> 00:30:49,848
Here it is, uh, HMS Taurean,
Trafalgar Class submarine,

541
00:30:49,931 --> 00:30:51,350
10 miles off the coast
of Plymouth.

542
00:30:51,600 --> 00:30:53,810
DOCTOR: Right,
we need to select a missile.

543
00:30:53,935 --> 00:30:56,021
We can't go nuclear.
We don't have the defence codes.

544
00:30:56,104 --> 00:30:58,273
We don't need it.
All we need is an ordinary missile.

545
00:30:58,565 --> 00:30:59,941
What's the first category?

546
00:31:00,609 --> 00:31:03,028
Sub harpoon, UGM-84A.

547
00:31:03,111 --> 00:31:04,529
That's the one! Select!

548
00:31:05,947 --> 00:31:07,532
I could stop you.

549
00:31:10,619 --> 00:31:11,870
Do it, then.

550
00:31:11,953 --> 00:31:13,455
DOCTOR: You ready for this?

551
00:31:16,416 --> 00:31:17,417
Yeah.

552
00:31:22,214 --> 00:31:25,509
Mickey the idiot,
the world is in your hands.

553
00:31:26,301 --> 00:31:27,427
Fire.

554
00:31:34,226 --> 00:31:35,519
(WHOOSHING)

555
00:31:37,062 --> 00:31:38,855
Oh, my God.

556
00:31:45,904 --> 00:31:47,322
(STEADY BEEPING)

557
00:31:51,159 --> 00:31:52,869
How solid are these?

558
00:31:52,953 --> 00:31:53,995
Not solid enough.

559
00:31:54,079 --> 00:31:56,331
Built for short-range attack.
Nothing this big.

560
00:31:57,082 --> 00:31:59,584
All right.
Now I'm making the decision.

561
00:31:59,668 --> 00:32:02,087
I'm not gonna die.
We're gonna ride this one out.

562
00:32:02,170 --> 00:32:03,755
It's like what
they say about earthquakes.

563
00:32:03,839 --> 00:32:06,007
You can survive them
by standing under a door frame.

564
00:32:06,091 --> 00:32:08,844
Now, this cupboard's small,
so it's strong.

565
00:32:08,969 --> 00:32:10,303
Come and help me.
Come on!

566
00:32:16,643 --> 00:32:18,019
The vote is in.

567
00:32:19,020 --> 00:32:20,522
The Council says...

568
00:32:22,732 --> 00:32:23,775
Yes.

569
00:32:24,192 --> 00:32:26,528
They are releasing the codes.

570
00:32:27,946 --> 00:32:29,823
Ring, damn you!

571
00:32:29,906 --> 00:32:31,908
-(RAPID BEEPING)
-It's on radar!

572
00:32:32,033 --> 00:32:33,869
MICKEY:
Counter defence 556.

573
00:32:33,952 --> 00:32:34,995
Stop them intercepting it!

574
00:32:35,078 --> 00:32:37,164
-I'm doing it now!
-Good boy.

575
00:32:40,375 --> 00:32:42,169
556 neutralised.

576
00:32:48,717 --> 00:32:50,719
What do you mean, "incoming"?

577
00:33:01,480 --> 00:33:04,691
-(ALARM SHRIEKS)
-Everybody out! Now! Now!

578
00:33:07,319 --> 00:33:09,112
What the hell is that for?

579
00:33:09,905 --> 00:33:11,239
Sir, there's a missile...

580
00:33:13,658 --> 00:33:14,826
Sorry!

581
00:33:30,592 --> 00:33:32,594
That's mine. You've got mine!

582
00:33:32,677 --> 00:33:34,554
Disguise me, disguise me!

583
00:33:35,639 --> 00:33:38,808
No, you're the blonde.
No, I've got the other one. Take it off!

584
00:33:41,853 --> 00:33:44,147
-(GUNSHOT)
-Everybody, run!

585
00:33:44,606 --> 00:33:47,067
MAN: Run!
Let's get out of here!

586
00:33:47,150 --> 00:33:48,693
(MISSILE SCREECHES)

587
00:33:53,782 --> 00:33:54,866
Here we go.

588
00:33:54,950 --> 00:33:57,369
Well, nice knowing you both.

589
00:33:59,788 --> 00:34:00,830
Hannibal!

590
00:34:02,415 --> 00:34:03,500
Oh, bol...

591
00:34:07,337 --> 00:34:08,547
(SHRIEKS)

592
00:34:10,131 --> 00:34:11,258
(GRUNTING)

593
00:34:38,827 --> 00:34:40,203
Made in Britain!

594
00:34:41,371 --> 00:34:42,956
Oh, my God. Are you all right?

595
00:34:43,039 --> 00:34:45,375
Harriet Jones,
MP, Flydale North.

596
00:34:45,458 --> 00:34:47,502
I want you to contact
the UN immediately.

597
00:34:47,627 --> 00:34:50,630
Tell the ambassadors
the crisis is over. They can step down.

598
00:34:51,548 --> 00:34:53,508
-Go on. Tell the news.
-Yes, ma'am.

599
00:34:53,633 --> 00:34:56,136
Someone's got a hell
of a job sorting this lot out.

600
00:34:57,304 --> 00:35:00,015
Oh, Lord! We haven't even got
a Prime Minister!

601
00:35:00,140 --> 00:35:03,727
-Maybe you should have a go.
-Me! I'm only a backbencher.

602
00:35:04,561 --> 00:35:05,937
I'd vote for ya.

603
00:35:06,021 --> 00:35:07,022
Now, don't be silly.

604
00:35:08,315 --> 00:35:10,400
Look, I'd better go
and see if I can help.

605
00:35:10,483 --> 00:35:12,110
-(EMERGENCY SIRENS APPROACH)
-Hang on!

606
00:35:15,071 --> 00:35:19,200
We're safe.
The Earth is safe!

607
00:35:22,245 --> 00:35:23,246
Sergeant!

608
00:35:23,330 --> 00:35:25,040
I thought I knew the name.

609
00:35:26,291 --> 00:35:27,792
Harriet Jones.

610
00:35:27,876 --> 00:35:29,544
-(SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY)
-Future Prime Minister.

611
00:35:29,628 --> 00:35:31,755
Elected for three
successive terms.

612
00:35:32,297 --> 00:35:34,341
The architect
of Britain's Golden Age.

613
00:35:34,424 --> 00:35:37,677
The crisis has passed!

614
00:35:37,761 --> 00:35:43,350
Ladies and gentlemen, I have something to
say to you all here today...

615
00:35:46,561 --> 00:35:49,564
Mankind stands tall,

616
00:35:49,648 --> 00:35:51,983
proud and undefeated!

617
00:35:53,276 --> 00:35:55,570
God bless the human race.

618
00:36:20,887 --> 00:36:23,723
(TARDIS CLANKS AND WHEEZES)

619
00:36:25,475 --> 00:36:28,770
HARRIET ON TV:
Mankind stands tall...

620
00:36:29,229 --> 00:36:32,357
Harriet Jones.
Who does she think she is?

621
00:36:32,440 --> 00:36:36,236
Look at her,
taking all the credit. It should be you on there.

622
00:36:36,528 --> 00:36:38,530
My daughter saved the world!

623
00:36:38,613 --> 00:36:40,281
I think the Doctor
helped a bit.

624
00:36:40,740 --> 00:36:43,159
All right, then.
Him, too.

625
00:36:44,452 --> 00:36:45,954
You should
be given knighthoods.

626
00:36:46,246 --> 00:36:47,706
It's not the way
he does things.

627
00:36:47,789 --> 00:36:49,999
No fuss, he just moves on.

628
00:36:51,167 --> 00:36:53,253
He's not that bad,
if you gave him a chance.

629
00:36:53,545 --> 00:36:55,880
He's good in a crisis,
I'll give him that.

630
00:36:55,964 --> 00:36:59,801
Oh! Now, the world has changed. You're
saying nice things about him.

631
00:36:59,968 --> 00:37:01,219
I reckon I've got no choice.

632
00:37:01,302 --> 00:37:03,847
There's no getting rid of him
since you're infatuated.

633
00:37:04,180 --> 00:37:05,849
I'm not infatuated!

634
00:37:06,307 --> 00:37:07,726
What does he eat?

635
00:37:07,809 --> 00:37:08,852
How do you mean?

636
00:37:08,935 --> 00:37:13,314
I was gonna do shepherd's pie.
All of us, proper sit-down.

637
00:37:14,524 --> 00:37:17,277
'Cause... (CLEARS THROAT)
I'm ready to listen.

638
00:37:17,736 --> 00:37:20,530
I want to learn
about you and him and that life you lead.

639
00:37:20,613 --> 00:37:22,657
I mean, I didn't know
he was an alien.

640
00:37:22,741 --> 00:37:26,327
For all I know, he eats grass
and safety pins, and things.

641
00:37:26,995 --> 00:37:28,580
He'll have shepherd's pie.

642
00:37:29,831 --> 00:37:31,166
You're gonna cook for him?

643
00:37:31,499 --> 00:37:32,625
What's wrong with that?

644
00:37:33,418 --> 00:37:35,128
He's finally met his match.

645
00:37:35,503 --> 00:37:38,173
-You're not too old for a slap, you know!
-(GIGGLES)

646
00:37:38,882 --> 00:37:40,800
You can go and visit
your gran tomorrow...

647
00:37:40,884 --> 00:37:42,677
-(MOBILE RINGING)
-...and learn some French.

648
00:37:42,802 --> 00:37:46,014
I told her you were in France.
I said you were au-pairing.

649
00:37:49,934 --> 00:37:51,102
Hello?

650
00:37:51,186 --> 00:37:53,438
Right, I'll be
a couple of hours, then we can go.

651
00:37:53,521 --> 00:37:54,731
You've got a phone!

652
00:37:54,939 --> 00:37:57,692
You think I can travel through space and
time and I haven't got a phone?

653
00:37:57,942 --> 00:38:00,028
Huh! Like I said,
couple of hours.

654
00:38:00,695 --> 00:38:02,697
I've just got
to send out this dispersal.

655
00:38:02,781 --> 00:38:03,782
There you go.

656
00:38:03,865 --> 00:38:05,742
That's cancelling out
the Slitheen's advert

657
00:38:05,825 --> 00:38:07,577
in case any bargain hunters
turn up.

658
00:38:09,579 --> 00:38:10,830
Um, my mother's cooking.

659
00:38:10,914 --> 00:38:12,582
Good. Put her on a slow heat
and let her simmer.

660
00:38:12,665 --> 00:38:14,834
She's cooking tea. For us.

661
00:38:15,210 --> 00:38:16,377
I don't do that.

662
00:38:16,461 --> 00:38:17,962
She wants to get to know you.

663
00:38:18,046 --> 00:38:19,506
Tough.
I've got better things to do.

664
00:38:19,589 --> 00:38:20,590
It's just tea.

665
00:38:21,424 --> 00:38:22,509
Not to me, it isn't.

666
00:38:22,592 --> 00:38:23,718
She's my mother.

667
00:38:23,843 --> 00:38:25,678
-Well, she's not mine.
-That's not fair!

668
00:38:25,929 --> 00:38:27,597
Well, you can stay there
if you want.

669
00:38:29,682 --> 00:38:32,894
But right now, there's this plasma storm
brewing in the Horsehead Nebula.

670
00:38:33,520 --> 00:38:35,939
Fires are burning,
10 million miles wide.

671
00:38:36,314 --> 00:38:38,900
I could fly the Tardis
right into the heart of it

672
00:38:39,025 --> 00:38:41,069
then ride the shock wave
all the way out.

673
00:38:41,236 --> 00:38:44,823
Hurtle right across the sky
and end up anywhere.

674
00:38:46,908 --> 00:38:48,201
Your choice.

675
00:38:53,832 --> 00:38:54,833
(DISCONNECTS)

676
00:39:01,506 --> 00:39:04,092
Rose, I was thinking...

677
00:39:05,593 --> 00:39:08,429
I've got that
bottle of Amaretto from New Year's Eve.

678
00:39:08,513 --> 00:39:09,514
Does he drink?

679
00:39:14,269 --> 00:39:16,104
I was wondering
whether he drinks or not.

680
00:39:16,229 --> 00:39:17,605
Yeah, he does.

681
00:39:23,611 --> 00:39:25,280
Don't go, sweetheart.

682
00:39:27,031 --> 00:39:28,491
Please don't go.

683
00:39:45,842 --> 00:39:46,885
Good lad.

684
00:39:46,968 --> 00:39:49,387
Graffiti that again
and I'll have ya. Now, beat it.

685
00:39:56,144 --> 00:39:57,520
I just went down the shop.

686
00:39:58,187 --> 00:40:01,524
And I was thinking,
you know, like, the whole world's changed.

687
00:40:01,858 --> 00:40:03,985
Aliens and spaceships
all in public.

688
00:40:06,321 --> 00:40:07,488
And here it is.

689
00:40:08,489 --> 00:40:10,700
How can they do that?
They saw it!

690
00:40:10,992 --> 00:40:13,703
You're just not ready. You're happy to
believe in something that's invisible,

691
00:40:13,828 --> 00:40:16,497
but if it's staring you
in the face, "Nope, can't see it!"

692
00:40:17,540 --> 00:40:20,209
There's a scientific
explanation for that. You're thick.

693
00:40:21,044 --> 00:40:22,170
(CHUCKLES)

694
00:40:22,670 --> 00:40:24,672
-We're just idiots.
-Well, not all of you.

695
00:40:26,090 --> 00:40:27,133
Yeah?

696
00:40:27,842 --> 00:40:29,010
Present for you, Mickey.

697
00:40:29,093 --> 00:40:30,428
That's a virus. Put it online,

698
00:40:30,511 --> 00:40:32,388
and it'll destroy
every mention of me.

699
00:40:32,472 --> 00:40:33,723
I'll cease to exist.

700
00:40:34,390 --> 00:40:36,225
-What do you want to do that for?
-'Cause you're right.

701
00:40:36,517 --> 00:40:39,228
I am dangerous.
I don't want anybody following me.

702
00:40:40,939 --> 00:40:43,024
How can you say that,
and then take her with you?

703
00:40:44,233 --> 00:40:46,611
You could look after her.
Come with us.

704
00:40:47,654 --> 00:40:48,738
I can't.

705
00:40:49,614 --> 00:40:51,115
This life of yours...

706
00:40:52,116 --> 00:40:54,202
It's just too much.
I couldn't do it.

707
00:40:56,120 --> 00:40:57,705
Don't tell her I said that.

708
00:40:58,039 --> 00:41:01,334
I'll get a proper job.
I'll work weekends, I'll pass my test.

709
00:41:01,417 --> 00:41:03,294
And if Jim comes round again,
I'll say no.

710
00:41:03,378 --> 00:41:05,797
-I really will.
-I'm not leaving 'cause of you.

711
00:41:05,880 --> 00:41:08,091
I'm travelling, that's all,
and then I'll come back.

712
00:41:08,174 --> 00:41:09,676
But it's not safe.

713
00:41:09,759 --> 00:41:13,888
Mum. If you saw it out there,
you'd never stay home.

714
00:41:16,849 --> 00:41:18,059
Got enough stuff?

715
00:41:18,393 --> 00:41:21,312
The first time
I stepped in there, it was spur-of-the-moment.

716
00:41:22,188 --> 00:41:25,191
Now I'm signing up.
You're stuck with me. (LAUGHS)

717
00:41:27,735 --> 00:41:29,737
Come with us.
There's plenty of room.

718
00:41:30,405 --> 00:41:33,032
No chance. He's a liability,
I'm not having him on board.

719
00:41:33,366 --> 00:41:34,742
We'd be dead without him.

720
00:41:35,034 --> 00:41:36,494
My decision is final.

721
00:41:38,663 --> 00:41:39,831
Sorry.

722
00:41:44,002 --> 00:41:45,044
Good luck, yeah?

723
00:41:45,128 --> 00:41:48,506
You still can't promise me.
What if she gets lost?

724
00:41:48,631 --> 00:41:50,675
What if something
happens to you, Doctor, and she's left

725
00:41:50,758 --> 00:41:53,886
all alone, standing on some
moon a million light years away?

726
00:41:54,095 --> 00:41:55,596
How long do I wait, then?

727
00:41:55,930 --> 00:41:59,434
Mum, you're forgetting.
It's a time machine.

728
00:41:59,517 --> 00:42:02,478
I could go travelling
around suns and planets

729
00:42:02,562 --> 00:42:04,439
and all the way
out to the edge of the universe,

730
00:42:04,522 --> 00:42:06,190
and by the time
we get back, yeah,

731
00:42:06,274 --> 00:42:09,569
10 seconds would have passed.
Just 10 seconds.

732
00:42:10,445 --> 00:42:12,071
So stop worrying.

733
00:42:12,488 --> 00:42:15,199
I'll see you
in 10 seconds' time, yeah?

734
00:42:38,723 --> 00:42:39,974
(WHIRRING)

735
00:42:59,827 --> 00:43:01,287
Ten seconds.

736
00:43:22,975 --> 00:43:25,645
ROSE: It's a great, big museum.
DOCTOR: An alien museum.

737
00:43:25,728 --> 00:43:26,771
Someone's got a hobby.

738
00:43:26,854 --> 00:43:29,482
The cage contains
my one living specimen.

739
00:43:29,774 --> 00:43:32,026
It must've fallen
through time. The only survivor.

740
00:43:32,110 --> 00:43:33,486
It's killing him.
Do something!

741
00:43:33,569 --> 00:43:36,280
I swear, no one
on this base is safe.

742
00:43:36,364 --> 00:43:37,615
You've got to keep it
in that cell.

743
00:43:37,698 --> 00:43:39,951
It can't get out.
That lock's got a billion combinations...

744
00:43:41,119 --> 00:43:42,662
Civilians! Let 'em through!

745
00:43:42,912 --> 00:43:45,832
That thing downstairs
is gonna kill every last one of us!

746
00:43:45,957 --> 00:43:47,750
-Where's the nearest town?
-Salt Lake City.

747
